You are welcome to use and modify the `spechomo` project.
See the README.rst and LICENSE files for details.

If you use this software for research we would appreciate appropriate citation.
This may be prepared using the bibliographic metadata contained in our DOI, accessible through the DOI system and at
https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678713

To cite the `spechomo` Python package in your publication, please use (modify the version number if needed):

  Scheffler, Daniel. (2020, April 3). SpecHomo: A Python package for spectral homogenization of multispectral satellite data (Version v0.6.0). Zenodo. https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678713

This may need modification for the citation style of your publication.
You are encouraged to include the version number of the software.

A BibTeX entry for LaTeX users should look like this
(find the one for the latest version here: https://zenodo.org/record/3739570/export/hx):

@software{scheffler_daniel_2020_3739570,
  author       = {Scheffler, Daniel},
  title        = {{SpecHomo: A Python package for spectral
                   homogenization of multispectral satellite data}},
  month        = apr,
  year         = 2020,
  publisher    = {Zenodo},
  version      = {v0.6.0},
  doi          = {10.5281/zenodo.3739570},
  url          = {https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3739570}
}

For information on citing software products generally, see the
FORCE11 document [*].


[*] FORCE11 Software Citation Working Group (2016), "Software Citation Principles", (Editors: Arfon M. Smith, Daniel S. Katz, Kyle E. Niemeyer).
    Accessed 2017-08-08 at https://www.force11.org/sites/default/files/shared-documents/software-citation-principles.pdf
